body_text:
Thanks @betanalpha for your in-depth comment!
I agree with most of your points. However, I think incorporating structure such as conditional independence is crucial. It's certainly crucial "for scaling statistical computation" (see, for example, the many works on scalable MCMC: Bardenet et al., 2015; Angelino et al., 2016; Andrieu and Roberts, 2009; Welling and Teh, 2011; Chen et al., 2014; Gelman et al., 2014; Maclaurin and Adams, 2014). Whether you believe in data subsampling is another thing (Betancourt, 2015), but I'm not sure if there are good alternative solutions.
@alexggmatthews: Having a standalone HMC algorithm in TensorFlow would be awesome. To avoid becoming part of a higher-level API, its scope has to be deliberately designed, both in what extensions it allows and what it limits.

body:
Thanks @betanalpha for your in-depth comment!

I agree with most of your points. However, I think incorporating structure such as conditional independence is crucial. It's certainly crucial "for scaling statistical computation" (see, for example, the many works on scalable MCMC: [Bardenet et al., 2015](https://arxiv.org/abs/1505.02827); [Angelino et al., 2016](https://arxiv.org/abs/1602.05221); [Andrieu and Roberts, 2009](https://projecteuclid.org/euclid.aos/1236693147); [Welling and Teh, 2011](http://www.icml-2011.org/papers/398_icmlpaper.pdf); [Chen et al., 2014](https://arxiv.org/abs/1402.4102); [Gelman et al., 2014](https://arxiv.org/abs/1412.4869); [Maclaurin and Adams, 2014](https://arxiv.org/abs/1403.5693)). Whether you believe in data subsampling is another thing ([Betancourt, 2015](https://arxiv.org/abs/1502.01510)), but I'm not sure if there are good alternative solutions.

@alexggmatthews: Having a standalone HMC algorithm in TensorFlow would be awesome. To avoid becoming part of a higher-level API, its scope has to be deliberately designed, both in what extensions it allows and what it limits.
